EKS shared clusters access
==========================

This VM contains EKS cluster information generated from Terraform outputs:
- /home/{{ ansible_hostname }}/.kube/config.eks
- /home/{{ ansible_hostname }}/.kube/config.eks.admin
- alias shell: eks='kubectl --kubeconfig /home/{{ ansible_hostname }}/.kube/config.eks'
- alias shell: admin-eks='kubectl --kubeconfig /home/{{ ansible_hostname }}/.kube/config.eks.admin'
- alias shell: eks-admin='kubectl --kubeconfig /home/{{ ansible_hostname }}/.kube/config.eks.admin'
- kubectl bash completion is enabled for aliases eks, admin-eks and eks-admin

Usage examples:
1) List available contexts:
   eks config get-contexts

2) Work in your namespace (default context cluster00, namespace={{ ansible_hostname }}):
   eks get pods

3) Query nodes on another context:
   eks --context cluster01 get nodes

4) Use cluster-admin kubeconfig (for advanced exercises only):
   admin-eks --context cluster00-admin get nodes
   # eks-admin is also available as an equivalent alias.

Notes:
- Each context in config.eks uses your own namespace and an AWS exec-based user profile (`aws eks get-token` with profile `eks`).
- This means `config.eks` refreshes EKS credentials automatically and normally no longer needs manual token rotation.
- /home/{{ ansible_hostname }}/.kube/config.eks.admin still uses a static admin token and may still need regeneration when it expires.
- Default context is cluster00 in /home/{{ ansible_hostname }}/.kube/config.eks.
{% if acme_certificates_enable | bool and tf_vars.eks_clusters is defined and tf_vars.eks_clusters.value is defined and (tf_vars.eks_clusters.value | length) > 0 %}
- Shared wildcard HTTPS is available on each cluster with a trusted certificate for hosts shaped like *.eksXX.{{ dns_subdomain }}.
- Example: myapp-{{ ansible_hostname }}.eks00.{{ dns_subdomain }} is covered, but front.{{ ansible_hostname }}-svc.eks00.{{ dns_subdomain }} is not covered by this wildcard because it uses multiple labels/subdomains before eks00.
- A secret named tls-certificate is copied into each student namespace on each cluster for explicit Ingress TLS exercises.
{% if eks_ingress_default_tls_certificate_enable | bool %}
- ingress-nginx is configured with the wildcard certificate as default SSL certificate.
{% else %}
- ingress-nginx is not configured with a default SSL certificate; students must explicitly reference tls-certificate in their Ingress TLS section.
{% endif %}
{% endif %}
